FY25 NPAT a miss but uranium price catalysts should see stock well supported; retain Overweight Key takeaways: 1) The FY25 EBITDA loss of - \(\) 17\(m was in - line with JPME, while elevated non - cash expenses saw the earnings loss of -\) 34m greater than JPME/BBG cons of - \(\) 11/- \(\) 14m\(on a more positive note, Honeymoon generated\) \ \(17.4m\) of free cashflow for the year; 2) BOE's balance sheet remains in good shape, with a net cash balance of \(\) 37m\(and a further\) \ \(5.5m\) in investments/liquid assets and \(\) 120m\(in inventories; 3) No changes were made to production and cost guidance from the JunQ result, with the independent review still pending. Following the result, our NPV is down 4% to\) \ \(2.14\) ps after adjusting corporate costs higher and our FY26 NPAT is down 7% to \(\) 77m\(after lowering Alta Mesa production slightly. With BOE screening with 10% potential upside to our\) \ \(2.15\) ps PT and uranium prices well supported as the market emerges from its seasonal lull, we retain our Overweight rating.
**FY25 Result - Earnings miss, but net cash in thec; $10.50/srPT, retain Neutral**

Key takeaways from the FY25 result: LEBITDA/NPAT misses of 10%/12% to consensus were primarily driven by higher costs, 3Net debt was broadly in line with JPMc/Cons, and 3) there were no changes to guidance provided with updates on the Karlawinda Expansion Project provided yesterday, highlighting good progress with first gold still targeted for SepQ26, and updates on schedule and capex still expected early DecQ. The growth outlook for CMM is the strongest in our coverage as KEP and Mt Gibson advance (+26% CAGR to FY29), but FCF is softer vs peers as a result (1% FY26/FY27 avg). Our PT moves marginally higher to $10.50/sh, but we retain our Neutral rating.

Iron ore & steelIron Ore & Steel - July steel output: China crude steel down \(3\%\) YTD, apparent demand off \(5\%\) , but pig iron has contracted just \(1\%\)
Iron ore- Price resilience amidst global turmoil; maintain \(\) 100\(/t for 2025
Australian iron ore - Oversold and showing significant value support; Overweight on all iron ore stocks
Aluminium Dashboard - Inventory falls to decade lows, global demand up \(2\%\) YTD
Copper Dashboard - China demand remains upbeat, but inventories up \(\sim 100kt\) in a month on strong supply growth
Lithium dashboard- China lithium chemical balance remains in surplus
Lithium - Global BEV sales up \(28\%\) YTD in June
Australian Mining- Perth Mining Meeting Feedback
Australian Gold Miners - Gold surges ahead of imminent rate cuts; pure play gold exposure preferred, upgrade NST to Overweight
Investor Positioning - Materials sector Underweight positioning increased 30bps; RIO and S32 now into the under- held category
Short Interest - Shorting across our coverage trends marginally lower; uranium, lithium and rare earths stay in the crosshairs
Spot Scenarios - FY26e MtM EBITDA upgrades narrow for the majors

Bannerman Energy - Large resource underpins a multi- decade mine life with potential to double production; initiate at OverweightLotus Resources- Next uranium producer, but execution risks elevated & valuation stretched; initiate at Underweight
Boss Energy- Australian uranium pure play with no debt & solid growth but valuation fair; Initiate at Neutral
Gold- Initiating on six gold names with Overweight; updating valuation methodology and LT gold price
MAC Copper- Copper pure play: single asset with growth via rising throughput and potential zinc by- product; initiate at Overweight
Paladin Energy - Solid growth outlook and attractive valuation metrics; initiate at Overweight
Capstone Copper - Pure copper exposure with strong growth and undemanding valuation metrics; initiate at Overweight
Mining- Outlining sector preferences after the panic selling
Australian Mining- Commodity review: iron ore solid while miners fall, FMG preferred; CSC stands out in copper, NST top gold pick
Uranium - Deep dive: Greenfield developments drive long- term supply surplus; market broadly balanced near term
Rio Tinto Ltd - Simandou advancing at pace; bringing first shipment forward to 1Q26
BHP and RIO - Deep dive: Comparing iron ore divisions - BHP makes more money on less tonnes; RIO FCF/t catches up next decade after Rhodes Ridge is built
